[[File:Demilitarized Zone of Korea 05.JPG|thumb|A set of [[Kim Il-sung]] and [[Kim Jong-il]] portraits]]
'''Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-il portraits''' are mandatory in [[North Korea]]n homes and some public places.

Visual depictions of [[Kim Il-sung]] have been commonplace in North Korea since the 1940s following the example of [[Joseph Stalin]] in the [[Soviet Union]] and [[Mao Zedong]] in [[China]]. The display of Kim Il-sung portraits was made mandatory at homes in the 1970s. Gradually, they have become mandatory in certain public places as well, such as factories, airports, railway stations, and rail and subway carriages. Portraits of [[Kim Jong-il]] have been hung next to Kim Il-sung since in the late 1970s. A portrait of [[Kim Jong-un]] was displayed for the first time in public in 2018.

Rules regarding the placement and maintenance of the portraits are complex and change frequently. At homes, they should be placed on the most prominent wall in the living room with nothing else on it, at high and looking downwards. Of importance, and subject to random checks, is that they are kept clean, a responsibility that usually falls on the lady of the house.

==History==
[[File:28.08.1946 Labour Party North Korea.jpg|thumb|Portrait of [[Kim Il-sung]] next to [[Stalin]] during the [[1st Congress of the Workers' Party of North Korea]] in 1946]]
[[File:Mangyongdae Children's Palace 09.JPG|thumb|Contemporary portraits on the exterior of a public building]]
[[File:People in Pyongyang Metro 01.JPG|thumb|Portraits on the [[Pyongyang Metro]]]]
[[File:Kim Il Sung University professorial housing complex (14142429880).jpg|thumb|Portraits of [[Kim Il-sung]], [[Kim Jong-il]], and [[Kim Jong-suk]]]]
Since the 1940s visual depictions of Kim Il-sung have been commonplace in North Korea.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}} The practice was adopted from [[Stalin]] portraits in the [[Soviet Union]] and portraits of [[Mao Zedong]] in [[China]].{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} Displaying a portrait of Kim Il-sung in every house became mandatory in the 1970s. The state distributed such portraits and instructed people to display them in their living rooms.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}} By Kim Il-sung's 60th birthday in 1972, North Korea had more leader portraits than the Soviet Union or China ever did.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} In 1972, the compulsory display of the portraits was extended to all factories, airports, and railway stations.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}}

At the end of the decade, North Koreans were told to hang portraits of Kim Jong-il next to their portraits of Kim Il-sung.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}} The regulation was put in place relatively late into Kim Jong-il's cult of personality.{{Sfn|Cha|2012|p=79}} The reason was that he had little, an by 1980 virtually no, competition as the heir apparent.{{Sfn|Cha|2012|pp=79, 87}} The order to do so became unofficially so that [[North Korean propaganda]] could claim that there was a spontaneous movement that supported Kim Jong-il. By around 1980, every office and home had the two portraits on display.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=53}} In the 1980s, the rules on portraits were extended yet again to cover rail and subway carriages. Buses and trams were excluded for unknown reasons.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}} Since the early 1990s, Kim Jong-il portraits have been the same size as those depicting Kim Il-sung, and their display has been standardized so that they are always displayed side-by-side.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} In the 1990s, a third kind of portrait was added that depicts Kim Jong-il and Kim Il-sung engaged in discussion about state management. High ranking officials were given yet another portrait, that of Kim Il-sung's first wife and mother of Kim Jong-il, [[Kim Jong-suk]]. Offices, however, do not display this picture.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=35}} In recent years, the portraits' societal importance has waned.{{Sfn|Do et al.|2015|p=238}}

The image of Kim Il-sung underwent changes as he aged and according to political currents: early portraits from the 1960s have him in a [[Mao suit]], while those from the 1980s depict him in a Western suit. Years after his death, he began to appear in the military uniform of ''[[Taewonsu]]'' (generalissimo). Images of Kim Jong-il, too, went from Mao suit to the ''Taewonsu'' uniform.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} Under [[Kim Jong-un]], the appearances of the portraits have become increasingly standardized.<ref name="nkne_Slog">{{Cite web |title=Slogans of the "Glorious Country" mass games, in pictures |work=NK News |date=13 September 2018 |access-date=15 September 2018 |url= https://www.nknews.org/gallery/slogans-of-the-glorious-country-mass-games-in-pictures/ }}</ref> A portrait of Kim Jong-un was displayed for the first time in public in November 2018 during a visit of [[Cuba]]n president [[Miguel Díaz-Canel]] to [[Pyongyang]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/north-korea-puts-kim-painting-on-show-for-first-time-10902190|title=North Korea puts Kim Painting on Show for the first time|date=6 November 2018|work=Channel NewsAsia|access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref>

North Korea expert [[Andrei Lankov]] notes that the set of rules regarding the portraits changes frequently, making it "remarkable for its constant fluidity".{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=27}}

==Display==
Today, the portraits are can be found everywhere in North Korea.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} Rules regarding the display and maintenance of the portraits are complex.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=53}} The portraits should be hung on the most prominent wall of the apartment with nothing else on it,<ref name="Hunter1999">{{cite book|last=Hunter|first=Helen-Louise|title=Kim Il-song's North Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lrz5OJvCkmIC&pg=PA16|year=1999|publisher=Praeger Publishers|location=Westport|isbn=978-0-275-96296-8|page=16}}</ref> preferably in the living room.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} They must be kept clean and may not be hung off-center.{{Sfn|Cha|2012|p=8}} Any disrespect to the images of the leaders is criminal. This includes not only portraits hung on walls but also e.g. images in newspapers.{{Sfn|Portal|2005|p=87}} Damage to the portraits leads to an investigating and, if the suspect is found guilty, punished.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=53}} A penalty of one day of hard labor at a construction site is reported for failure to properly hang the portraits.{{Sfn|Do et al.|2015|p=238}} The portraits are to be protected even in the case of an emergency.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=36}} Still, neglecting care for the portraits is considered a rather minor offense, and as such, it is a typical confession that people make during [[mutual criticism session]].{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|pp=42–44}} Random checks for the portraits are carried out,{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=27}} monthly at least during Kim Il-sung's reign,<ref name="Senker2012">{{cite book|last=Senker|first=Cath|title=North Korea and South Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0K6w7OU0MpUC&pg=PA12|year=2012|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4488-6072-2|page=12}}</ref> but the ''[[inminban]]'' (neighborhood watch) sometimes tips people off of inspections.{{Sfn|Do et al.|2015|p=238}}

When a North Korean changes apparent, he or she must start by hanging the portraits first.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=27}} The portraits are usually hung on a wall with nothing else, placed high, and looking downwards. Some families bow to the portraits every morning and in the evening,{{Sfn|Portal|2005|p=87}} saying greetings,<ref name="KwonChung2012"/> even though bowing to them is not mandatory even in public placers.<ref name="Hunter1999"/> When a North Korean family mourns a dead member, ceremonial greetings and offerings are made to the deceased, but only after the two portraits have been given the same treatment.<ref name="KwonChung2012"/> The portraits are usually kept clean by adults in the house, typically the mother of the family. They wipe the glass every morning. Sometimes the portraits have a box under them that houses a white cloth used for dusting them that one is not allowed to use for any other purpose.<ref name="KwonChung2012">{{cite book|last1=Kwon|first1=Heonik|last2=Chung|first2=Byung-Ho|title=North Korea: Beyond Charismatic Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PGKJeXLSM3EC&pg=PA143|year=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|location=Lanham|isbn=978-1-4422-1577-1|page=143}}</ref>{{Sfn|Portal|2005|p=87}}

In addition to homes, offices, factories, shops, hospitals, classrooms and libraries sport the portraits,{{Sfn|Portal|2005|p=87}} as do decks of ships and fronts of trains.<ref name="Hunter1999"/> In public buildings they are placed above the main entrances.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}} All portraits are made by the [[Mansudae Art Studio]]. They are glazed and framed with timber.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}}

==Saving==
Stories about North Koreans saving leader portraits from certain destruction have been sported in [[North Korean media]] for decades,{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=53}} and they have also been disseminated by the ''inminban''.{{Sfn|Do et al.|2015|p=237}} For instance, in 2007 it was reported that a factory worker rescued his leader portraits and his five-year-old daughter from a flooded house. When he was overpowered by the water, he let go of his daughter but managed to hold onto the portraits.{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=36}} Such a feat can rise the societal status of a person considerably by improving his or her ''[[songbun]]'' (ascribed social rank in North Korea).{{Sfn|Lankov|2015|p=44}} Saving portraits is based on an arbitrary interpretation of the [[Ten Principles for the Establishment of a Monolithic Ideological System]].{{Sfn|Do et al.|2015|p=237}}

==Special portraits==
In addition to the standardized portraits, there have been special cases. One of these is a gift from the [[Syrian Arab Republic]], a portrait of Kim Il-sung that is entirely made up of [[Arabic calligraphy]] of his work ''[[The Non-Aligned Movement is a Mighty Anti-Imperialist Revolutionary Force of Our Times]]'', housed at the [[International Friendship Exhibition]].{{Sfn|Portal|2005|p=95}} The largest Kim Il-sung portrait, at least in Pyongyang, was 15 by 11 meters and was hung at the [[Pyongyang Department Store No. 1]] in the 1990s.{{Sfn|Lankov|2007|p=26}}

